PK, isko bhi Evolution of Pain + Feynman style me samjhte hain. Yeh actually very common System Design interview question hai:

“Ticket booking / flash sale / concert sale system crash kyun hota hai?”

1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Disaster Scenario)

Imagine:

Coldplay concert tickets
Sale opens → 12:00 PM

At exactly 12:00 PM

1 million users click "Book Ticket"

At the same second.

What system looks like normally

Typical architecture:

Users
   │
   ▼
Load Balancer
   │
   ▼
Ticket Service Instances
   │
   ▼
Database

Example:

Ticket Service
 ├── Instance 1
 ├── Instance 2
 └── Instance 3

Each instance has:

Thread pool
Queue

Example capacity:

100 threads
500 queue size
2️⃣ Nightmare Moment (Thundering Herd)

At 12:00 PM

1,000,000 requests arrive instantly

System capacity:

300 threads
1500 queue slots

So:

Remaining 998,200 requests fail

This problem is called:

Thundering Herd Problem

Meaning:

Huge traffic spike at same instant

Examples where this happens:

concert booking

flash sales

IPO trading

ticket booking

product launch

3️⃣ System Starts Collapsing

Step by step disaster:

Step 1

Queues become full.

Instance1 Queue → FULL
Instance2 Queue → FULL
Instance3 Queue → FULL
Step 2

Requests rejected.

HTTP 503
timeout
connection refused
Step 3 (Very Dangerous)

Clients retry.

Example:

User retry
Browser retry
Mobile retry
SDK retry

Now traffic becomes:

1M original requests
+ 1M retries
+ 1M retries again

Now system receives:

3M requests
4️⃣ Cascading Failure

Another problem happens.

When system overloaded:

CPU high
Memory high
Thread pool exhausted

Latency increases.

Example:

Normal:

Request time = 10 ms

Overloaded:

Request time = 2 sec

Because requests stay in queue.

Then timeouts start

Client waits.

timeout after 3 sec

Client thinks:

Request failed

Client retries.

Now again traffic doubles.

This creates:

Retry Storm

Very common production failure.

5️⃣ Why Auto Scaling Doesn't Save You

You might think:

Auto scaling will fix it

But no.

Reason:

Auto scaling takes time.

Example:

scale decision = 30 sec
new instance boot = 1 minute

But traffic spike happens in:

1 second

So system crashes before scaling helps.

6️⃣ Solutions (Real Production Solutions)
Solution 1 — Exponential Backoff

Instead of retrying immediately.

Clients wait.

Formula:

wait = base × 2^n

Example:

retry1 = 200ms
retry2 = 400ms
retry3 = 800ms
retry4 = 1600ms

This slows retries.

Problem with Backoff

If everyone retries with same formula.

All clients retry at same time

Still creates spike.

7️⃣ Solution 2 — Jitter

Add randomness.

Instead of fixed retry.

Use:

retry_time = random(0 , base × 2^n)

Example:

Client 1:

retry in 300ms

Client 2:

retry in 450ms

Client 3:

retry in 120ms

Traffic spreads.

8️⃣ Solution 3 — Rate Limiter (Most Important)

Add API Gateway Rate Limiter.

Architecture becomes:

Users
  │
  ▼
API Gateway
  │
  ▼
Rate Limiter
  │
  ▼
Load Balancer
  │
  ▼
Ticket Services
Token Bucket Algorithm

Example:

System capacity:

5000 req/sec

Token bucket allows only:

5000 tokens

Only those requests proceed.

Remaining:

wait
or reject

This protects backend.

9️⃣ Better Architecture for Ticket Booking

Production systems do this:

Users
   │
   ▼
CDN
   │
   ▼
API Gateway
   │
   ▼
Rate Limiter
   │
   ▼
Queue (Kafka/SQS)
   │
   ▼
Ticket Booking Workers
   │
   ▼
Database

Queue smooths traffic.

10️⃣ Best Technique (Used by BookMyShow)

Instead of allowing instant booking.

They create Virtual Queue.

Example:

User enters queue
Position = 25342

Then users allowed gradually.

Example:

500 users per second

This avoids thundering herd.

11️⃣ Real Systems Using This

Systems that face this problem:

BookMyShow

Ticketmaster

IRCTC

Flipkart Big Billion Day

Amazon Prime Day

All implement:

Rate limiting
Queues
Backoff + jitter
Virtual waiting rooms
12️⃣ Mental Model (Important for Interviews)

When you see:

Flash sale
Ticket booking
Stock trading

Immediately think:

Thundering Herd
Retry Storm
Queue overload

Solutions:

Rate limiter
Backoff + jitter
Queue buffering
Virtual waiting room